## 🧠 PART 3 — Tech Stack Deep Dive

### 3.1 RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) — The Core Concept

> [!info] What RAG is
> A pattern where an LLM is given relevant external knowledge at query time to generate grounded answers. Instead of relying on what the LLM "knows," it retrieves facts from your documents and answers based on them.

**Why RAG matters:**
- LLMs have knowledge cutoffs and limited internal knowledge
- LLMs hallucinate when they don't know
- You can't easily teach an LLM private data (PCI-DSS, internal docs)
- RAG injects fresh, specific context per question

**RAG vs Fine-Tuning:**

| Aspect | RAG | Fine-Tuning |
|---|---|---|
| Cost | Low | High |
| Speed to update | Instant (re-index) | Slow (retrain) |
| Hallucination | Low (grounded) | Still possible |
| Best for | Q&A over documents | Style/behavior adaptation |

**RAG Pipeline (memorize):**
1. **Ingest** — load documents
2. **Chunk** — split into pieces
3. **Embed** — convert to vectors
4. **Store** — index in vector DB
5. **Query** — embed user question
6. **Retrieve** — find similar chunks
7. **Augment** — add chunks to prompt
8. **Generate** — LLM produces answer

**Interview prep:**
- *"What is RAG?"* → Retrieval-Augmented Generation. LLM is given relevant context at query time, generates answers grounded in that context
- *"When would you use RAG over fine-tuning?"* → When data changes often, when you need source attribution, when you can't afford training compute
- *"Why not just stuff all documents in the prompt?"* → Context windows are limited (typically 8K-128K tokens), cost scales with input size, attention degrades on long contexts

