### 3.8 Recursive Character Text Splitter (Chunking Strategy)

> [!info] What it is
> A LangChain text splitter that tries to keep semantically related text together. Splits on natural boundaries (paragraphs → sentences → words → characters) hierarchically.

**Your chunking strategy:**
- **chunk_size = 1000** characters
- **chunk_overlap = 200** characters (20%)

**Why these values:**
- 1000 chars ≈ 250 words ≈ 1 paragraph — captures meaningful units
- 200 chars overlap prevents losing context at boundaries
- Standard defaults that work for most documents

**Splitting hierarchy:**
1. First try splitting on `\n\n` (paragraphs)
2. If chunks still too big, split on `\n` (lines)
3. Then on `. ` (sentences)
4. Finally on ` ` (words)
5. Last resort: character-level

**Why hierarchical:**
- Preserves semantic boundaries
- A chunk is usually a coherent paragraph rather than a random window
- Better retrieval quality

**Interview prep:**
- *"Why chunk size 1000?"* → Captures roughly one paragraph or one coherent section. Smaller (200-500) is good for precise retrieval; larger (2000+) is good for context-heavy questions. 1000 is a good default
- *"Why 200 char overlap?"* → Prevents losing context at chunk boundaries. If a key sentence is split across two chunks, overlap ensures one of them has the full sentence
- *"Alternatives to character-based chunking?"* → Token-based (using tokenizer), semantic chunking (split where embedding similarity drops), document-aware (split on headers, sections). All have tradeoffs

