## 🎤 PART 5 — Common Interview Questions

### Q1: Walk me through your AcquirerX Compliance Assistant end-to-end

> AcquirerX Compliance Assistant is a personal project I built to demonstrate hands-on RAG skills. It's a local, fully offline RAG-powered assistant that answers questions about payment compliance documents — PCI-DSS and RBI guidelines.
>
> The architecture has two phases. In the indexing phase, I load PDFs with PyPDF, chunk them using LangChain's RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter with chunk size 1000 and overlap 200, embed each chunk with the all-MiniLM-L6-v2 model from sentence-transformers, and store the resulting 384-dimensional vectors in a FAISS index.
>
> At query time, the FastAPI app receives a question, the question is embedded with the same model, FAISS retrieves the top 4 most similar chunks, those chunks are stuffed into a prompt template with explicit instructions to only use the provided context, and the prompt is sent to a local LLM running on Ollama — llama3.2:3b. The response is parsed and returned as JSON with the answer and source citations.
>
> Everything runs locally — no API calls, no cloud, no data leakage. That's deliberate because compliance documents are sensitive.

### Q2: What is RAG and why did you use it?

> RAG stands for Retrieval-Augmented Generation. The idea is to give an LLM relevant context at query time so it generates grounded answers instead of hallucinating from its training data.
>
> For compliance Q&A, RAG is the right choice because the documents are private (not in the LLM's training data), they change occasionally (would need re-fine-tuning), and accuracy matters (you can't make up regulations). RAG also gives you traceable citations — you can tell the user which page of which document the answer came from.

### Q3: Walk me through your chunking strategy

> I used LangChain's RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter with chunk_size=1000 characters and chunk_overlap=200. The recursive part is important — it tries to split on natural boundaries hierarchically: first paragraphs, then sentences, then words, then characters as a last resort. This preserves semantic coherence within chunks.
>
> 1000 chars roughly captures one paragraph or one coherent section. 200 chars of overlap prevents losing context at chunk boundaries — if a key sentence falls right where chunks split, the overlap ensures one chunk has the full sentence. These are well-tested defaults that work for most documents.

### Q4: Why FAISS over Pinecone or Chroma?

> Three reasons. First, it's free and runs locally — no API costs, no network calls, no external dependencies. Second, it's fast — FAISS is the gold standard for similarity search, used by Meta in production. Third, my corpus is small (2-3 PDFs, maybe a few thousand chunks), so I don't need the persistence or scaling features of Pinecone or Chroma. For a production system at scale, I'd probably switch to Qdrant or Pinecone for managed scaling, but FAISS is perfect for this use case.

### Q5: Which embedding model and why?

> all-MiniLM-L6-v2 from sentence-transformers. 384 dimensions, 80 MB on disk, runs fast on CPU, produces strong embeddings for general semantic search. It's a great balance of speed, size, and quality. For higher quality, I'd use bge-base or bge-large, but those are slower. For commercial scale, OpenAI's text-embedding-3 produces 1536-dimensional vectors with even better quality, but it's a paid API and sends data externally — not great for compliance docs.

### Q6: Why local LLM (Ollama) instead of OpenAI?

> Compliance documents can be sensitive. Sending them to OpenAI means data leaves my machine and goes to a third party — not great for trust or for actual production deployment in regulated industries. Ollama runs the LLM entirely locally on my laptop. No data leaves the machine. No API costs. No rate limits. Works offline. The tradeoff is quality — a 3B parameter local model isn't as good as GPT-4, but it's good enough for grounded Q&A where the context does most of the heavy lifting.

### Q7: How do you prevent hallucinations?

> Multiple layers. First, RAG itself — by providing context, the model has facts to ground in. Second, my prompt template explicitly instructs the model to "use ONLY the provided context" and "say I don't have enough information" if the context doesn't contain the answer. Third, temperature is set to 0 for deterministic outputs. Fourth, structured JSON response means the model can't just freeform. For a production system, I'd add automated evaluation with RAGAS to measure faithfulness and answer relevance, plus human-in-the-loop review for critical answers.

### Q8: What's the difference between RAG and fine-tuning?

> RAG adds external knowledge at query time. Fine-tuning bakes knowledge into model weights through training. Different tools for different problems.
>
> RAG is right when your data changes often, when you need source citations, when training compute is expensive, or when documents are private (PCI-DSS, internal docs).
>
> Fine-tuning is right when you need to change model behavior or style, when the knowledge is stable, when you can afford training, and when retrieval latency is unacceptable.
>
> For a compliance assistant, RAG is clearly the right choice — docs update, citations matter, no training data needed.

### Q9: What's a context window and how did you handle it?

> Context window is the maximum number of tokens an LLM can process in one call. For llama3.2:3b, it's 8192 tokens. I have to fit prompt + retrieved context + space for the answer.
>
> My retrieved context is 4 chunks × 1000 chars ≈ 4000 chars ≈ 1000 tokens. Prompt template is another ~200 tokens. Question is ~50 tokens. That leaves around 7000 tokens for the answer, which is way more than I need. So my design fits comfortably within the context window.

### Q10: How would you scale this to handle 10,000 documents?

> A few changes. First, I'd switch FAISS to use HNSW indexing instead of flat — much faster for large corpora. Or move to a managed vector DB like Qdrant or Pinecone for built-in persistence, replication, and metadata filtering. Second, add async processing for ingestion — embedding 10K documents takes time, parallelize it. Third, add reranking — after retrieving top 20 chunks with vector search, rerank with a cross-encoder for higher quality top-k. Fourth, add hybrid search — combine BM25 keyword search with vector search for better recall. Fifth, scale the LLM — switch to a larger model on a GPU server, or route to OpenAI for higher quality (if compliance allows). Sixth, add caching — semantic cache for repeated questions. Finally, add evaluation pipeline with RAGAS to track quality over time.

### Q11: Why FastAPI over Flask?

> FastAPI is faster (async support out of the box), it auto-generates OpenAPI/Swagger docs which is great for API exploration, and it uses Pydantic for request/response validation — so you get type safety and automatic input validation. Plus its modern async model handles concurrent requests better, which matters when LLM calls take a few seconds. Flask works fine, but FastAPI is just better for modern API development.

### Q12: What evaluation did you do?

> Honest answer — I didn't run formal evaluation metrics on this project. I manually tested with a set of compliance questions and reviewed the answers against the source PDFs. In a more rigorous setup, I'd use RAGAS to measure faithfulness (does the answer match retrieved context?), answer relevance (does it address the question?), context precision and recall. I'd also build a golden test set of questions with known correct answers for regression testing.

### Q13: How would you integrate this into AcquirerX?

> Two patterns. First, **service-to-service integration** — wrap the FastAPI as a microservice in the AcquirerX architecture. Spring Boot services call it for compliance lookups. Add Resilience4J circuit breakers and retries around the calls. Use the existing JWT auth flow. Second, **embedded chatbot** — expose it as a chat interface in the AcquirerX admin UI so operations and compliance teams can query compliance docs directly. Either way, MDC trace IDs would propagate so we can debug across the existing distributed tracing setup.

